args: Please note that this story contains spoilers\nfor chapter 5 of the main campaign.
Let me out! Please, I...\nI gotta get out of this village!
Talk about a ghost town.\nThere's not a soul in sight.

Here's hoping incorporeality doesn't
correlate with inhospitality. Oh, ghooosts!
Cassandra thirsts—some water, please!
...Hm?
Thunder. The rain won't be far behind.
I suppose we'll have to wait it out in this\nabandoned house. And just when I'd finally\ngathered the last ingredient, too.
Water, lime, saltpeter, sulfur... I thought\nwe were buildin' a human, not fertilizing\nthe lawn! Zing!
Really? This again? The theory is sound.\nMy procedure should yield a perfectly\nserviceable vessel.

Then what? We get back to the workshop
and you turn that hibiscus you picked into
a batch of soul-summoner's incense?
Bing, bang, conjure the dead, boom?
His soul is fused with the Shadowwyrm's\nmana. If we tease it apart with the incense\nand transfer it into a waiting vessel...
You get a cool zombie that looks just like\nyour old flame. Zing!

We're not talking about tryin' to cram a
soul back in its old box like a certain
queen we won't mention. This is playing
Frankenstein for your own selfish reasons.

Ain't sorcerer-ing supposed to be all about
understanding profound laws and guiding
nature along its course? What you're doin'
here flies in the face of all that.
I'm well aware it's taboo, thank you.\nThat isn't about to—
I'm just saying, you've already GOT a guy.
Who, Audric? He has his own dumb court\nsorceress in the world he came from.\nShe gets dibs.
Besides, no one could ever replace the\nman I spent all those years with.
So you're just gonna dive head-first into\nheresy? What happened to your pride as a\nsorcer—
Feh! I see how it is. Silly me,\nforgetting you're a senile old bag with\nmore wrinkles 'n I got dog-eared pages.

I'm aware that my tenacity in this
particular pursuit is unbecoming.
But if there's any chance of this
working, I'm going to try it.
I won't give up again like\nI did that summer...
You're inviting me to a festival?
One of the villages I'm set to look in on is\nholding an event in Hinomotoan fashion.\nWould you accompany me on my visit?
If you like. A court sorceress's place is at\nher king's side.
Who all is coming with us?\nRaemond, I would imagine, and—
No. I've other important matters\nto entrust to Raemond.

My royal guard will be on security detail
for the event as well. I'd hate to disrupt
the locals by marching a grand entourage
through.
Ah, so it's to be a date! Never pegged\nyou for the sort. This ought to be fun.
We're there to work, Cassandra. I want\nyour thoughts on this influx of foreign\ncultural influence.
Fine, fine. I'm sure having a grumpy king\nwandering through their midst won't stop\nthe locals from enjoying their party at ALL.
I think it's important to enjoy the festival\nas your people do, sire. Don't you worry—\nI will teach you to have a grand old time.
Hmm... I suppose there's something to\nthat. I leave the matter to you, then.
Heh heh. There's a good boy. Now,\nrun along. We've a big day ahead!
Aaand there! Managed to get the obi tied.
Quite the fetching look, these Hinomotoan\nyukatas. It was worth the trouble of hunting\none down.
This ought to drag a compliment\nout of him.
No. It's a Hinomotoan festival. There's no\nlogical argument to be made against\nwearing a yukata.
Besides, the man wouldn't know fun if it\nhatched from a dragon egg and called him\n＂papa.＂
It's going to be just the two of us...\nI'd assert that I'm showing remarkable\nrestraint.
Pardon the intrusion, milady. I wanted to\nspeak with you about the visitation plans.
Yes, of course. What is it?
I'm afraid that heavy rains have\nflooded the roads. We'll need to\nadjust our departure schedule.
Regrettably, this means we'll have to\ngive up on attending the festival.
Is that so? Well, scheduling is up to you\nministers and Aurelius. Why come to me?
His Majesty said we might still keep to our\noriginal plans if we were willing to risk it.\nPersonally, I can't recommend it, but...
Ah. He's being stubborn on my account.

You go and tell him that if he does
something stupid and the unthinkable
happens, he'll have made fools of his
entire court!
Tsk. All dressed up and nowhere to go.\nHis loss, I suppose.
I played the good sport about it, but even now,\nregret lingers like a thorn in my heart.
I wonder what he would have said\nupon seeing me in such fetching attire...
Was I asleep? Goodness, I must\nhave been tuckered out if—hm?
This is...the yukata from back then!\nWhy in the world am I in it now? I'd\nbanished it to the back of my closet.
Am I still dreaming?\nBut the sensation is so real...
Give me a reality check, Douleur.\nAm I wearing a yukata right now?
Oh, stop your sulking and answer me.\n...Douleur?
Gone. I don't see how a mouthy diary could\nhave sprouted legs and walked off on his—
Hm. Voices. And not just a few...
What is going on here?\nThis village was completely deserted.
Look at you, all gussied up! Come all\nthe way to our little hamlet to take in\nthe summer festival, have you?
Oh, how marvelous!\nYou enjoy yourself, now.
Do you live here? I have a laundry list of\nquestions. What is this place? Where...
(Wait. This preternatural sensation...\nAh! These people must be—!)
